(33, 17, 'Our summer reads1', 'Reading is a time-honored pleasure, and in the heat of our hectic and all-consuming schedules, moments spent alone with a book are like gold and dust. In light of that fact, we have saved you some valuable time with our recommended reading list for the summer. Happy perusing and enjoy these rare moments.\r\n', '<p>Reading is a time-honored pleasure, and in the heat of our hectic and all-consuming schedules, moments spent alone with a book are like gold and dust. In light of that fact, we have saved you some valuable time with our recommended reading list for the summer. Happy perusing and enjoy these rare moments.</p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 10px 0;"><img alt="" src="./pic/cv/uploads/20130730/1375180110.png" style="float:left; height:230px; width:200px" />\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 0 10px;max-width:470px;float:left;"><strong>A SONG OF ICE AND FIRE</strong>, George R.R.Martin, 1996 - 2013<br />\r\n<br />\r\nYou may be more familiar with its TV show format &lsquo;Game of thrones&rsquo; which took its title from the first book of this epic fantasy, but the books offer a far more insightful and brilliant immersion into R.R. Martin&rsquo;s pseudo-medieval fantasy phenomenon. Worth making the time for.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;the great fantasy epic of our era.&rdquo; TIME Magazine 2011</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="clear:both;height:1px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 10px 0;"><img alt="" src="./pic/cv/uploads/20130730/1375180135.png" style="float:left; height:282px; width:200px" />\r\n<div style="margin:20px 0 0 10px;max-width:470px;float:left;"><strong>I LOVE NEW YORK</strong>, Daniel Humm and Will Guidara, April 2013<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis is an exploration of so much more than cooking. A cookbook that aims to showcase New York&rsquo;s great heritage and unique cuisine like you have never known it.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;In I Love New York, Humm and Guidara present an in-depth look at the region&rsquo;s centuries-old farming traditions along with nearly 150 recipes that highlight its outstanding ingredients. Lushly illustrated with photographs of the area&rsquo;s dramatic landscapes and the farmers who tend the land, this unique ode introduces the concept of New York regional cuisine as it celebrates the bounty of this exceptional state.&rdquo; Random House 2013</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="clear:both;height:1px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 10px 0;"><img alt="" src="./pic/cv/uploads/20130730/1375180123.png" style="float:left; height:282px; width:200px" />\r\n<div style="margin:8px 0 0 10px;max-width:470px;float:left;"><strong>THE NEW DIGITAL AGE</strong>, Eric Schmidt and Jared Cohen, 2013<br />\r\n<br />\r\nConsidering that the current debate about online privacy and security has become part of our daily dialogue, Google&rsquo;s Executive Chairman, Eric Schimdt and co-writer Jared Cohen&rsquo;s &ldquo;The New Digital Age&rdquo; is an essential read of the moment.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;a sober examination of what current technological trends mean for our future. That includes the ability of repressive governments to turn every smartphone into a bugging device; the breakdown of privacy; the danger of countries setting up their own, censored versions of the internet; the threat of hackers, terrorists and cyber-warfare; and, at root, the fact that people and governments will have to function in both the real and virtual worlds, which will not just overlap but collide.&rdquo; The Telegraph 2013</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="clear:both;height:1px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 10px 0;"><img alt="" src="./pic/cv/uploads/20130730/1375180094.png" style="float:left; height:282px; width:200px" />\r\n<div style="margin:18px 0 0 10px;max-width:470px;float:left;"><strong>THE OLD MAN AND THE SEA</strong>, Ernest Hemingway, 1952<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHemingway&rsquo;s last prominent work to be published, about an unfortunate old fisherman in Cuba, prompted the entire re-evaluation of Hemingway&rsquo;s work and brought him great critical acclaim. It was awarded the Pullitzer Prize for Fiction 1953 and The Nobel Prize in Literature in 1954.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;The Nobel Prize in Literature 1954 was awarded to Ernest Hemingway &quot;for his mastery of the art of narrative, most recently demonstrated in The Old Man and the Sea, and for the influence that he has exerted on contemporary style&rdquo; The Nobel Foundation 1954</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="clear:both;height:1px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 10px 0;"><img alt="" src="./pic/cv/uploads/20130730/1375180081.png" style="float:left; height:282px; width:200px" />\r\n<div style="margin:20px 0 0 10px;max-width:470px;float:left;"><strong>SEVEN AMERICAN DEATHS AND DISASTERS</strong>, Kenneth Goldsmith, June 2013<br />\r\n<br />\r\nKenneth Goldsmith is the author of this book. But &ldquo;Seven American Deaths and Disasters&rdquo; was written by the voices of newsreaders who had to break the some of America&rsquo;s most catastrophic events to the world. A compelling read.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;Goldsmith has also delivered a kind of found treasure of the American vernacular. His book is about the sounds our culture makes when the reassuring smooth jazz of much of our broadcast media breaks down, when disc jockeys and news anchors are forced to find words for events that are nearly impossible to describe. This book is about language under duress&rdquo; New York Times 2013</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="clear:both;height:1px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'en_us'),
(34, 17, 'OUR SUMMER READS2', 'Reading is a time-honored pleasure, and in the heat of our hectic and all-consuming schedules, moments spent alone with a book are like gold and dust. In light of that fact, we have saved you some valuable time with our recommended reading list for the summer. Happy perusing and enjoy these rare moments.\r\n', '<p>Reading is a time-honored pleasure, and in the heat of our hectic and all-consuming schedules, moments spent alone with a book are like gold and dust. In light of that fact, we have saved you some valuable time with our recommended reading list for the summer. Happy perusing and enjoy these rare moments.</p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 10px 0;"><img alt="" src="/pic/cv/uploads/20130730/1375180110.png" style="float:left; height:230px; width:200px" />\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 0 10px;max-width:470px;float:left;"><strong>A SONG OF ICE AND FIRE</strong>, George R.R.Martin, 1996 - 2013<br />\r\n<br />\r\nYou may be more familiar with its TV show format &lsquo;Game of thrones&rsquo; which took its title from the first book of this epic fantasy, but the books offer a far more insightful and brilliant immersion into R.R. Martin&rsquo;s pseudo-medieval fantasy phenomenon. Worth making the time for.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;the great fantasy epic of our era.&rdquo; TIME Magazine 2011</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="clear:both;height:1px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 10px 0;"><img alt="" src="/pic/cv/uploads/20130730/1375180135.png" style="float:left; height:282px; width:200px" />\r\n<div style="margin:20px 0 0 10px;max-width:470px;float:left;"><strong>I LOVE NEW YORK</strong>, Daniel Humm and Will Guidara, April 2013<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis is an exploration of so much more than cooking. A cookbook that aims to showcase New York&rsquo;s great heritage and unique cuisine like you have never known it.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;In I Love New York, Humm and Guidara present an in-depth look at the region&rsquo;s centuries-old farming traditions along with nearly 150 recipes that highlight its outstanding ingredients. Lushly illustrated with photographs of the area&rsquo;s dramatic landscapes and the farmers who tend the land, this unique ode introduces the concept of New York regional cuisine as it celebrates the bounty of this exceptional state.&rdquo; Random House 2013</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="clear:both;height:1px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 10px 0;"><img alt="" src="/pic/cv/uploads/20130730/1375180123.png" style="float:left; height:282px; width:200px" />\r\n<div style="margin:8px 0 0 10px;max-width:470px;float:left;"><strong>THE NEW DIGITAL AGE</strong>, Eric Schmidt and Jared Cohen, 2013<br />\r\n<br />\r\nConsidering that the current debate about online privacy and security has become part of our daily dialogue, Google&rsquo;s Executive Chairman, Eric Schimdt and co-writer Jared Cohen&rsquo;s &ldquo;The New Digital Age&rdquo; is an essential read of the moment.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;a sober examination of what current technological trends mean for our future. That includes the ability of repressive governments to turn every smartphone into a bugging device; the breakdown of privacy; the danger of countries setting up their own, censored versions of the internet; the threat of hackers, terrorists and cyber-warfare; and, at root, the fact that people and governments will have to function in both the real and virtual worlds, which will not just overlap but collide.&rdquo; The Telegraph 2013</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="clear:both;height:1px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 10px 0;"><img alt="" src="/pic/cv/uploads/20130730/1375180094.png" style="float:left; height:282px; width:200px" />\r\n<div style="margin:18px 0 0 10px;max-width:470px;float:left;"><strong>THE OLD MAN AND THE SEA</strong>, Ernest Hemingway, 1952<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHemingway&rsquo;s last prominent work to be published, about an unfortunate old fisherman in Cuba, prompted the entire re-evaluation of Hemingway&rsquo;s work and brought him great critical acclaim. It was awarded the Pullitzer Prize for Fiction 1953 and The Nobel Prize in Literature in 1954.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;The Nobel Prize in Literature 1954 was awarded to Ernest Hemingway &quot;for his mastery of the art of narrative, most recently demonstrated in The Old Man and the Sea, and for the influence that he has exerted on contemporary style&rdquo; The Nobel Foundation</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="clear:both;height:1px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin:10px 0 10px 0;"><img alt="" src="/pic/cv/uploads/20130730/1375180081.png" style="float:left; height:282px; width:200px" />\r\n<div style="margin:20px 0 0 10px;max-width:470px;float:left;"><strong>SEVEN AMERICAN DEATHS AND DISASTERS</strong>, Kenneth Goldsmith, June 2013<br />\r\n<br />\r\nKenneth Goldsmith&rsquo;s is indeed the author of this book. But &ldquo;Seven American Deaths and Disasters&rdquo; was written by the voices who had to break the some of America&rsquo;s most catastrophic events to the world.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&ldquo;Goldsmith has also delivered a kind of found treasure of the American vernacular. His book is about the sounds our culture makes when the reassuring smooth jazz of much of our broadcast media breaks down, when disc jockeys and news anchors are forced to find words for events that are nearly impossible to describe. This book is about language under duress&rdquo; New York Times</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="clear:both;height:1px;">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'zh_cn'),
